      • isNaN

        public boolean isNaN(Script<?> script,
            java.lang.Object... args)

        Tests whether a value is the not-a-number value, simulating the JavaScript global function of the same name.

        In JavaScript, This function tests its argument to determine whether it is the value NaN, which represents an illegal number (such as the result of division by zero). This function is required because comparing a NaN with any value, including itself, always returns false, so it is not possible to test for NaN with the == or === operators.

        A common use in JavaScript of this function is to test the results of parseFloat(Script, Object[]) and parseInt(Script, Object[]) to determine if they represent legal numbers. You can also use isNaN(Script, Object[]) to check for arithmetic errors, such as division by zero

        Parameters:
        script - The script context that invoked this service
        args - An array of the arguments passed by the invocation
        Returns:
        true if v is (or can be converted to) the special not-a-number value; false if v is any other value.
        Since:
        Descripter 1.0

      • parseInt

        public int parseInt(Script<?> script,
           java.lang.Object... args)

        Parses an integer from a string, simulating the JavaScript global function of the same name.

        In JavaScript, this function parses and returns the first number (with an optional leading minus sign) that occurs in value. Parsing stops, and the value is returned, when it encounters a character in value that is not a valid digit for the specified radix. If value does not begin with a number that it can parse, the function returns the not-a-number value NaN. Use the isNaN(Script, Object[]) function to test for this return value.

        Parameters:
        script - The script context that invoked this service
        args - An array of the arguments passed by the invocation
        Returns:
        The parsed number, or NaN if value does not begin with a valid integer. In JavaScript 1.0, this function returns 0 instead of NaN when it cannot parse value.
        Since:
        Descripter 1.0

      • parseFloat

        public double parseFloat(Script<?> script,
                java.lang.Object... args)

        Parses a number from a string, simulating the JavaScript global function of the same name.

        In JavaScript, this function parses and returns the first number that occurs in value. Parsing stops, and the value is returned, when it encounters a character in value that is not a valid part of the number. If value does not begin with a number that it can parse, the function returns the not-a-number value NaN. Test for this return value with the isNaN(Script, Object[]) function. If you want to parse only the integer portion of a number, use parseInt(Script, Object[]) instead of this one.

        Parameters:
        script - The script context that invoked this service
        args - An array of the arguments passed by the invocation
        Returns:
        The parsed number, or NaN if value does not begin with a valid number. In JavaScript 1.0, this function returns 0 instead of NaN when value cannot be parsed as a number.
        Since:
        Descripter 1.0
